<header class="doc-page-header">
  <span class="eyebrow">Recipe &middot; Refactoring</span>
    <h1 style="margin-top:1rem;">How to <em>refactor safely</em> with AI agents</h1>
    <p class="doc-hero__sub">
      <strong>TL;DR:</strong> An AI agent renaming an exported function
      will, by default, miss the dynamic callers, ESM-only re-exports, and
      barrel files that grep doesn't find. Use
      <code>file_preflight</code> + <code>imports_impact</code> +
      <code>reef_diff_impact</code> + diagnostics to see the full blast
      radius before and after the edit. Tools used: <code>file_preflight</code>,
      <code>imports_impact</code>,
      <code>imports_hotspots</code>, <code>ast_find_pattern</code>,
      <code>reef_diff_impact</code>, <code>lint_files</code>,
      <code>typescript_diagnostics</code>, <code>git_precommit_check</code>.
    </p>
</header>
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <article class="doc-body" style="max-width: 78ch;">

      <section>
        <h2>The scenario</h2>
        <p>You want to rename <code>getUserById(id)</code> to
        <code>fetchUser(id)</code>. The function is in
        <code>lib/users/queries.ts</code> and is used "everywhere" — but
        you don't actually know how many callers there are or what shape
        they take.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>The vanilla approach (and why it falls over)</h2>
        <p>An AI agent without an import graph reaches for grep:</p>
        <pre><code>$ rg -n "getUserById" .</code></pre>
        <p>That misses:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Re-exports through barrels: <code>export &lcub; getUserById &rcub; from "../users/queries"</code> renamed to <code>fetchUser</code> downstream.</li>
          <li>Default-export callers that import as <code>import getUser from "..."</code>.</li>
          <li>Dynamic <code>import()</code> patterns.</li>
          <li>Test mocks at <code>__mocks__/lib/users/queries.ts</code>.</li>
          <li>Generated client SDKs that re-export from <code>queries.ts</code>.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The agent renames the source, "all tests pass" (because the
        mocks shadow the real module), and three days later production
        breaks for the SDK consumers.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>The agentmako approach</h2>

        <h3>Step 1 — <code>file_preflight</code></h3>
        <p>Before editing the file, ask Reef what is already known about
        it:</p>
        <pre><code>&lcub;
  "tool": "file_preflight",
  "args": &lcub; "filePath": "lib/users/queries.ts", "limit": 50 &rcub;
&rcub;</code></pre>
        <p>This returns active findings, diagnostic stale flags, recent
        runs that covered the file, applicable conventions, and any ack
        history. You learn whether a warning is new or already reviewed
        before the agent rewrites the code.</p>

        <h3>Step 2 — <code>imports_impact</code></h3>
        <p>Ask the index "what depends on this file?"</p>
        <pre><code>&lcub;
  "tool": "imports_impact",
  "args": &lcub; "filePath": "lib/users/queries.ts", "limit": 200 &rcub;
&rcub;</code></pre>
        <p>Returns every indexed file that imports anything from
        <code>queries.ts</code>, including re-export chains. You learn
        there are 47 direct importers, 11 of them re-exports through
        <code>lib/users/index.ts</code>, and 3 generated SDK files under
        <code>packages/sdk/</code> that you would have missed entirely.</p>

        <h3>Step 3 — <code>imports_hotspots</code></h3>
        <pre><code>&lcub;
  "tool": "imports_hotspots",
  "args": &lcub; "limit": 30 &rcub;
&rcub;</code></pre>
        <p>Tells you which of those importers are themselves widely used.
        If <code>lib/users/index.ts</code> is imported by 120 other files,
        that's the file you want to update first to keep the
        re-export name surface stable.</p>

        <h3>Step 4 — <code>ast_find_pattern</code></h3>
        <p>Catch the patterns grep can't:</p>
        <pre><code>&lcub;
  "tool": "ast_find_pattern",
  "args": &lcub;
    "pattern": "getUserById($A)",
    "languages": ["ts", "tsx"],
    "maxMatches": 200
  &rcub;
&rcub;</code></pre>
        <p>Structural search returns every actual call site as an AST
        match, with file paths and line ranges. Each match has an
        <code>ackableFingerprint</code> if you want to mark intentional
        legacy uses.</p>

        <h3>Step 5 — diagnostics before edits</h3>
        <pre><code>&lcub;
  "tool": "typescript_diagnostics",
  "args": &lcub; "files": ["lib/users/queries.ts", "lib/users/index.ts"] &rcub;
&rcub;</code></pre>
        <p>Get a clean baseline. If TSC reports issues unrelated to your
        rename, you'll know they were pre-existing — not caused by the
        refactor.</p>

        <h3>Step 6 — make the edits, then check diff impact</h3>
        <p>Rename in source, update the barrel re-exports, update the
        SDK files. Then ask what your working-tree diff may have affected:</p>
        <pre><code>&lcub;
  "tool": "reef_diff_impact",
  "args": &lcub; "filePaths": ["lib/users/queries.ts", "lib/users/index.ts"] &rcub;
&rcub;</code></pre>
        <p>Re-run <code>typescript_diagnostics</code> on the
        same files. Compare findings: any new ones are caused by the
        refactor.</p>

        <h3>Step 7 — pre-commit gate</h3>
        <pre><code>&lcub;
  "tool": "git_precommit_check",
  "args": &lcub;&rcub;
&rcub;</code></pre>
        <p>Catches staged route auth and boundary regressions before you
        ship.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Variations</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>API surface change (not just a rename):</strong>
          add <code>cross_search</code> for the old name across schema,
          RPCs, and routes — sometimes a "function name" leaks into a
          DB function or a Next.js route.</li>
          <li><strong>Breaking change you can't avoid:</strong> use
          <code>imports_impact</code> output as a downstream PR list.
          Each downstream owner gets a focused PR rather than a single
          giant one.</li>
          <li><strong>Public package:</strong> after the in-repo edits,
          add a deprecation shim that re-exports the old name with
          <code>@deprecated</code>. Use <code>file_preflight</code> on the
          shim to catch acks, conventions, and diagnostics that flag it
          for removal in a later release.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Tools used in this recipe</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><code>file_preflight</code> — pre-edit findings, diagnostic freshness, conventions, and acks.</li>
          <li><code>imports_impact</code> — files that depend on a file.</li>
          <li><code>imports_hotspots</code> — most widely-imported files in the project.</li>
          <li><code>ast_find_pattern</code> — structural ast-grep over indexed JS/TS/TSX.</li>
          <li><code>reef_diff_impact</code> — changed-file downstream impact and convention risks.</li>
          <li><code>lint_files</code> — Mako rule-pack diagnostics.</li>
          <li><code>typescript_diagnostics</code> — TSC diagnostics persisted into Reef.</li>
          <li><code>git_precommit_check</code> — staged TS/TSX boundary checks.</li>
          <li><code>cross_search</code> — search a term across code, schema, RPC, routes, memories.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

